\begin_layout Abstract

\series bold
Step 1.
 Study the features in this document.

\series default
 Please read through this Abstract.
 It is intended to be readable, pleasant, welcoming and helpful.
 The PDF you are reading was created by compiling thesis-ku.tex.
 After you finish inspecting this document, then look at the LaTeX document
 from which it came.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\series bold
Step 2.
 Inspect the LaTeX source code that is provided in the same package as the
 PDF document.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
There are some special features that will become apparent once you look
 at the LaTeX source code.
 The thesis-ku document is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

master
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 document.
 The separate chapters are in separate folders.
 It is possible to work on one chapter at a time, and compile just that
 chapter, or it is possible to compile the whole thing by compiling the
 master document.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In thesis-ku, we have included as many bells and whistles as possible so
 that users can see how the different features can be put to use.
 We have a BibTeX bibliography, graphs, equations, cross references, table
 of contents, and all of the other interesting features.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The most recently inserted feature is support for hyperlinks in the PDF
 output.
 We checked with the KU Graduate Dean's office and they said there is no
 policy prohibiting the use of hyperlinks, but there is also no guarantee
 from the dissertation hosting institution that they will either work or
 not cause problems down the line.
 We believe there is not too much danger here, this feature is easy to turn
 off if need be.
 Also, it is not entirely clear what color the links must be inside the
 document, so we take a conservative step here of making the links black,
 so they appear as simple text.
 The default settings for the 
\family typewriter
hyperref
\family default
 package, which we have altered, caused ugly pink links with gross looking
 boxes around them.
 Users can change the link color to blue.
 It is fairly easy to see how this can be done in the document preamble.
 Look for something like this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
urlcolor={black},citecolor={black},allcolors={black}
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\family default
 and think of Henry Ford's famous comment, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You can have a car in any color you like, as long as its black.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

